'''''All Hope Is Gone''''' is the fourth [[studio album]] by American [[Heavy metal music|metal]] band [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]. It was released on August 20<!-- Released in Japan on 20th, SEE TALK PAGE -->, 2008,<ref name="Japan release"/> by [[Roadrunner Records]]. A special edition of the album contains three bonus tracks, and is packaged in a six-fold [[digipak]] with a 40-page deluxe booklet<ref name="Japan release">{{cite news |title = All Hope is Gone (w/ DVD, Limited Edition) |publisher = CD Japan|date = 2008-07-10 |url = http://www.cdjapan.co.jp/detailview.html?KEY=RRCY-29152 |accessdate = 2008-07-11}}</ref> and bonus DVD containing a documentary of the album's conception.<ref name="BonusDVD">{{cite news |title = Slipknot Announce Special Edition Album |publisher = ''Metal Hammer'' |date = 2008-07-29 |url = http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/article/?id=48737 |accessdate = 2008-07-29}}</ref>

Noted to have begun preparation in 2007, recording was due to begin in January 2008; however, it was delayed to February.<ref>{{cite video |people = [[Mick Thomson]] |title = NAMM 2008 Report |publisher = MySpace.com | work=Ontrackmagazine.com |url= http://www.opiumofthepeople.net/ootp/main.php?go=micknamm|accessdate=2008-08-23}}</ref> It is the band's first studio release since 2004's ''[[Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)]]'', making ''All Hope Is Gone'' their fourth studio album as well as the first musical output from the band since [[Corey Taylor]] and [[James Root|Jim Root]]'s mainstream success with [[Stone Sour]]; [[Joey Jordison]]'s stints with [[Korn]], [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]] and [[3 Inches of Blood]]; [[Shawn Crahan]]'s side project [[Dirty Little Rabbits]]; and [[Sid Wilson]]'s solo project. ''All Hope Is Gone'' is also the band's first studio album released by a [[Record label#Major labels (music groups)|major label]] to be recorded in their home state of [[Iowa]].<ref name="MTV">{{cite news |title = Slipknot's Clown On 'Psychosocial' Video: 'Our Goal Has Always Been To Infect' |publisher = [[MTV News]] |date = 2008-07-17 |url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1591102/20080717/slipknot.jhtml |accessdate = 2008-08-10}}</ref>

==Recording and production==
Preparation for ''All Hope Is Gone'' reportedly began in 2007, drummer [[Joey Jordison]] explains; "I've told them to demo whatever they can so we've got as much material to chose from as possible."<ref>{{cite news| title=Slipknot man promises brutal new album in '08| url=http://www2.kerrang.com/2007/07/slipknot_man_promises_brutal_n.html|date=2007-07-20| accessdate=2007-11-29|publisher = Emap}}</ref> In February 2008,<ref>{{cite web |author = [[Mick Thomson|Thomson, Mick]] |title = NAMM 2008 Report |publisher = On Track Magazine |url= http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&videoid=29777240|accessdate=2008-07-14}}</ref> Slipknot entered the [[Sound Farm Studio & Recording Environment|Sound Farm Studio]] in [[Jamaica, Iowa|Jamaica]], [[Iowa]] with producer [[Dave Fortman]].<ref name="RevAugust">{{cite journal |last = Epstein |first = Dan |year = 2008 |month = August |title = Wait and Bleed |journal = [[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]] |pages = 54-6 |accessdate = 2008-06-14}}</ref> Unlike any of their previous albums, ''All Hope Is Gone'' was written and recorded in the band's home state of Iowa. Bassist [[Paul Gray]] explained that they decided to do this because in [[Los Angeles]] <U+2014> where all their previous albums were produced <U+2014> there are too many distractions.<ref>{{cite web |title = Slipknot brings Mayhem |work = AZCentral.com |publisher = ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' |date = 2008-07-16 |url = http://www.webcitation.org/5ZY09Zt6s |accessdate = 2008-07-24}}</ref> Band members also revealed that it was good for their mindset being so close to home, in an interview with ''[[Kerrang!]]'', vocalist [[Corey Taylor]] revealed that he would make a point of driving home every night to see his son.<ref name="K!JulySpecial">{{cite news |title = We are Slipknot and somebody's gonna get killed... |work = [[Kerrang!]] |pages = 22-27 |publisher = [[Emap]] |date = 2008-07-26}}</ref> Of the album's production Jordison said, "it's finally the record that I've wanted Slipknot to sound like." Complimenting Fortman's ear for tone, he explains that he believes that this is the band's best album sonically.<ref>{{cite web |title = Metal Hammer Podcast Is Live |publisher = [[Metal Hammer]] |date = 2008-07-24 |url = http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/article/?id=48715 |format = [[Podcast]] |accessdate = 2008-07-24}}</ref> The album was mixed by [[Colin Richardson]] in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news |last = Wilcox |first = Daniel |title = The Great Rock News Report |publisher = 411mania |date = 2008-07-16 |url = http://www.411mania.com/music/columns/80407/The-Great-Rock-News-Report-07.16.08.htm |accessdate = 2008-07-25}}</ref>

[[Image:Crahan All Hope Is Gone DVD.jpg|thumb|left|[[Shawn Crahan]] during the recording sessions of the album]]
Unlike previous releases, all nine band members were involved in the writing process of the album, reportedly writing over 30 songs. Jordison reveals, "I have to say that the band is at its peak; everyone<U+2014>I mean everyone<U+2014>is now completely involved in the writing process, and it's a beautiful thing."<ref name="RevAugust"/> When questioned about the process, vocalist Taylor explained that the cycle was not met without conflict. He went on to add that the creation of every Slipknot album has had conflict and that the band has come to embrace it, as they realize it is what brings out their creativity.<ref name="CoreyInterview">{{cite web |title = Exclusive Podcast: Slipknot<U+2019>s Corey Taylor Raises the Flag Before Setting it Aflame |publisher = MTV |date = 2008-07-04 |url = http://headbangersblog.mtv.com/2008/07/04/exclusive-podcast-slipknots-corey-taylor-raises-the-flag-before-setting-it-aflame-addresses-mayhem-fest-new-record/ |accessdate = 2008-07-07}}</ref> Also for the first time, some members of the group separated themselves from the band to write some tracks. Vocalist Taylor and guitarist [[James Root|Jim Root]] paired up with turntablist [[Sid Wilson]] (performing on keyboards) and percussionist [[Shawn Crahan]] (who took up full drumming duties) to work on what was described as "oblique, arty pieces."<ref name="RevAugust"/> One experiment saw Taylor tracking in an old well, he enthused, "there was this natural reverb to it that was just intense."<ref name="RevAugust"/> Crahan would later reveal that none of these tracks made it on to the album. However, one of which, "Til We Die" does appear as a bonus track on the special edition.<ref>{{cite web |last = Harris |first = Chris |title = Slipknot's Clown Unmasks Band's Trademark Look: How Often Are Those Masks Cleaned Anyway? |publisher = MTV |date = 2008-07-21 |url = http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1591189/20080718/slipknot.jhtml |accessdate = 2008-07-24}}</ref> During an interview with LiveDaily, guitarist Root expressed some discontent over the process of the record, stating that "it felt a little bit rushed. And it felt like we were trying to do things just to appease a schedule, which I didn't really like." On the subject of the record's producer, Root went on to say, "Dave Fortman really helped me appreciate Rick Rubin as a producer," and that, "[Fortman] wasn't able to get nine people together on the same page and, to me, that's the most important thing in making a Slipknot record."<ref> {{citeweb |url=http://www.livedaily.com/news/14643.html |title=LiveDaily Interview: Jim Root of Slipknot |accessdate=2008-08-10 |publisher=LiveDaily |date=2008-07-31}}</ref>  In an interview in the October 2008 issue of  ''[[Guitar World]]'', Root went as far as saying that Fortman didn't produce the album, adding; "I'd honestly have to say that he was really just a good engineer. He didn't do what I'm used to with producers."<ref name="GW-oct08">{{cite book |title = The Futility of Hope |publisher = ''[[Guitar World]]'' |date = October 2008 |pages = 61-66}}</ref>  He then again expressed his frustration with the way the album came together, saying "I don't want to make another album the way we made this one; I just don't think it's a good way to make a record.  I might as well have stayed at my house in Florida, and we could have [[FTP]]'d files back and forth."<ref name="GW-oct08"/>

Prior to the release of ''All Hope Is Gone'', copies of the album intended for reviewers were pressed under the false name "Rusty Cage," in order to reduce risks of the album [[Internet leak|leaking]] to the [[Internet]] early.<ref>{{citeweb |url=http://www.thrashhits.com/2008/08/album-slipknot-all-hope-is-gone/ |title=Album: Slipknot - All Hope Is Gone |accessdate=2008-08-20 |publisher=Thrash Hits |date=2008-08-13}}</ref>

==Promotion==
[[Image:Slipknot1.jpg|right|thumb|The first splash teaser picture.]]
It rumored that, due to the members being unmasked in their side projects, Slipknot was going to be recording and touring this album unmasked. However, these rumors have been dismissed by many band members. Percussionist Shawn Crahan addressed this issue during an interview on [[The Sauce (Fuse TV Series)|The Sauce]] when discussing the release of their 2006 DVD release ''[[Voliminal: Inside the Nine]]''.<ref name="TheSauce">{{cite episode| title = Shawn Crahan Interview| series = The Sauce| serieslink = The Sauce (Fuse TV Series)| airdate = 2007-04-23}}</ref> Bassist [[Paul Gray (Slipknot)|Paul Gray]] confirmed during an interview that the band will be returning with a new image; regarding the masks, he stated, "It'll still be Slipknot, but we're gonna upgrade, step things up a little."<ref name="K!Jan08">{{cite news |title = What time is it? Slipknot time! |work = [[Kerrang!]] |pages = 29 |publisher = [[Emap]] |date = 2008-01-05}}</ref> Beginning on April 1, 2008, Slipknot's official website began to display splash teasers to promote ''All Hope Is Gone''.<ref>{{cite news |title = Slipknot: First Glimpse At New Masks |publisher = [[Blabbermouth.net]] |date = 2008-04-01 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=93999 |publisher=Roadrunner Records| accessdate = 2008-06-17}}</ref> 10 teaser trailers were released. The first nine displayed the band in their new large masks, however the latest seemingly shows dark figures with what seems like ordinary size heads.<ref>{{cite web |title = Slipknot official site |date = 2008-06-06 |url = http://www.slipknot1.com |accessdate = 2008-06-28}}</ref> Slipknot premiered their new masks on July 1, 2008 through AOL Music's [[Spinner.com]]; 8 million people logged onto the site to view the masks on the first day.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= SLIPKNOT: 8 Million People Log On To AOL To See New Masks|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=100127 |work= |publisher= [[Blabbermouth.net]]|date= 2008-07-03|accessdate=2008-07-03}}</ref> In July 2008, Slipknot became the third band to have each member pictured on a special edition cover of [[Kerrang!]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www2.kerrang.com/2008/07/slipknot_in_next_weeks_kerrang.html|title= Slipknot: In next week<U+2019>s Kerrang! magazine|accessdate=2008-07-17 |publisher= [[Kerrang!]]|date= 2008-07-16}}</ref>

[[Image:Jim Root Mayhem.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Guitarist James Root performing during the [[Mayhem festival]] in New York City.]]

On June 15, a 30-second sample and cover art from the album's title track, "[[All Hope Is Gone (song)|All Hope Is Gone]]," was available on [[Amazon.com]].<ref>{{cite news |title = Slipknot: New Single Sample, Artwork Available |publisher = Blabbermouth.net |date = 2008-06-15 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=99064 |accessdate = 2008-06-17}}</ref> The title track began [[Airplay (radio)|airplay]] on the same day, and on June 20, for a single day, Roadrunner Records posted a download-able version of the title track, in its entirety, for free download and was released as a [[Paid download|digital single]] soon after. The second single from the album, "[[Psychosocial (song)|Psychosocial]]" began airplay on June 26, and was released as a digital single on July 7.<ref name="FreeSingleFriday">{{cite web |url= http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=99274|title= SLIPKNOT To Release Free Single On Friday|accessdate=2008-06-18 |publisher= [[Blabbermouth.net]]|date= 2008-06-18}}</ref>

The album cover art and track listing was released on July 8,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=100526|title= SLIPKNOT: 'All Hope Is Gone' Artwork Revealed|accessdate=2008-07-08 |publisher= Blabbermouth.net|date= 2008-07-08}}</ref> the day before the band started their first tour since 2005 on the [[Mayhem festival]] across the [[United States]]. The Mayhem festival is scheduled to last until August 16. Slipknot was scheduled to appear at [[Reading and Leeds Festivals]] in [[England]], the Two Days a Week Festival in [[Austria]] and the Area4 Festival in [[Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=97309|title= SLIPKNOT: European Festival Appearances Announced|accessdate=2008-07-13 |publisher= Blabbermouth.net|date= 2008-05-19}}</ref> However, Joey Jordison broke his ankle and the European tour dates were canceled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/hi/music/newsid_7573000/7573008.stm|title=Slipknot pull out of UK festival|accessdate=2008-08-21 |publisher=BBC.com|date= 2008-08-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title= A Statement from Slipknot|publisher= Roadrunner Records|date= 2008-08-20|url= http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/artists/Slipknot/index.aspx?newsitemID=19447|accessdate= 2008-08-21}}</ref> Overall, the tour for the album is expected to surpass that of ''Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)''{{'}}s, which featured 233 concerts spanning 28 months throughout 34 countries.<ref name="Voliminal">{{cite video |title = Voliminal: Inside the Nine |accessdate = 2008-07-14 |year = 2006 |people = Shawn Crahan (Director) |publisher = Roadrunner Records |medium = DVD}}</ref>

''[[Kerrang!]]'' has announced six special listening events spanning the [[United Kingdom]] which were hosted from August 17 through August 19. These events included a preview of the documentary supplied with special editions of the album, ''Nine: The Making of All Hope Is Gone'', as well as free merchandise.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www2.kerrang.com/2008/08/slipknot_hear_the_new_album_fi.html|title= Slipknot, hear the new album first|accessdate=2008-08-10 |publisher= Kerrang|date= 2008-08-06}}</ref>

==Musical and lyrical themes==
For ''All Hope Is Gone'', the band displayed interest in making it their heaviest album to date.<ref name=MH-CoreyInterview>{{cite news | title=Corey Taylor: Metal Hammer exclusive| url=http://www.metalhammer.co.uk/news/article/?id=46905|date=2007-08-06| accessdate=2007-12-02|publisher = Future Publishing}}</ref> The band made an expansion on the [[thrash metal]] riffing that was displayed on ''Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)'', as well as adding additional guitar solos.<ref name=MH-CoreyInterview/> However, they also wanted to make it their most experimental record, and have included more acoustic guitars and melodic vocals.<ref>{{cite news |author = Dan |title = Slipknot man promises brutal new album in '08 |publisher = Emap |date = 2007-07-20 |url = http://www2.kerrang.com/2007/07/slipknot_man_promises_brutal_n.html |accessdate = 2007-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title = Slipknot's Clown Talks About Upcoming Album |publisher = Blabbermouth.net |date = 2008-01-09 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=88079 |accessdate = 2008-01-10}}</ref> During an interview in the February 2008 edition of ''[[Revolver (magazine)|Revolver]]'', percussionist Crahan expressed a willingness for him and fellow percussionist [[Chris Fehn]] to experiment with hi-hats and cymbals which has been absent in the additional percussion in any previous work.<ref name="RevFeb08">{{cite news |title = Slipknot's Clown Talks About Upcoming Album |publisher = Blabbermouth |date = 2008-01-09 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=88079 |accessdate = 2008-01-10}}</ref> In an interview on May 13, 2008, singer Corey Taylor described ''All Hope Is Gone'' as a "very dark" combination of the band's two most recent studio albums, ''Iowa'' and ''Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)''.<ref name=RipFace/>
{{cquote2|quotetext=It's going to rip your face off...I don't think the world will be ready for this album.|personquoted=Corey Taylor<ref name=RipFace>{{cite news |first= Mitchell |last= Peters|title= Taylor: New Slipknot Album Will 'Rip Your Face Off'|url=http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1003802532 |publisher= Billboard.com|date= 2008-05-13|accessdate=2008-05-14 }}</ref>}}
Taylor, whose lyrics have traditionally been about his life, stated this album's lyrics will be less about his life and more, "bitching about what's wrong in life."<ref name=RipFace/> Crahan said that the album is different than their first three because it was made "by a bunch of crazy guys in their 30s. That doesn't mean we're slowing down or not as intense <U+2014> our brains are different, so we're bringing different emotions, different feelings and different anxieties to the table now. This record is another diagnosis of our insanity."<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1588339/20080529/slipknot.jhtml|title= Slipknot's Clown Tells Rockstar Tourmates 'Get Out Of Our Way'|accessdate=2008-05-30 |author= Chris Harris|date= 2008-05-30|work= |publisher=MTV}}</ref> Taylor would later say of the album, "I think it's the best thing I've ever made."<ref>{{cite news |title = Slipknot Percussionist Talks About New Single 'Psychosocial' |publisher = Blabbermouth.net |date = 2008-06-19 |url = http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=99384 |accessdate = 2008-06-20}}</ref> During an interview in June 2008 Taylor explained that the album title was aimed at the fans expectations of the band, stating; "All hope of trying to figure us out is completely obliterated."<ref name="CoreyInterview"/> When questioned about the musical outlook of the album Taylor explained that the band has retained some of the melodic elements that they experimented with on ''Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)'', but implies that ''All Hope Is Gone'' is much darker and edgier.<ref name="CoreyInterview"/>

==Reception==
Anticipation for the band's fourth studio album began upon the release of Slipknot's previous album, ''Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)'', when [[Allmusic]] stated, "there's a sense that whatever Slipknot do next might be their ultimate broadcast to the faithful."<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/cg/amg.dll?p=amg&sql=10:dnfuxqtaldfe~T1|title= Vol. 3: The Subliminal Verses - Review|accessdate=2008-06-15 |author= Johnny Loftus|date= |work= |publisher=[[Allmusic]]}}</ref> The percussive edge on the album was praised by ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' reviewer Chris Steffen, "the band<U+2019>s multiple percussionists generate a din that<U+2019>s more suffocating than ever" on the track "Gematria." He went on to propose that "Snuff" the "most melodic" song on the album, comparing it to "''Vol. 3: (The Subliminal Verses)''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s" "Circle." The album's second single, "Psychosocial," "is capped off with a time-signature shattering guitar/drum breakdown that will leave the best air-instrumentalists stumped."<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.rollingstone.com/rockdaily/index.php/2008/06/20/new-slipknot-album-a-first-listen-to-all-hope-is-gone/|title= New Slipknot Album: A First Listen to <U+201C>All Hope Is Gone<U+201D>|accessdate=2008-06-23 |author= Chris Steffen|date= 2008-06-08|work= |publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> The album was praised by ''[[Total Guitar]]'' writer Nick Cracknell, who declared the effort, "Slipknot's heaviest and most aggressive work to date," comparing "Dead Memories" to the works of [[Alice in Chains]], while praising "Gehenna" for being the band's "most experimental work in their history." He went on to state "Wherein Lies Continue" contains a "huge chugging verse riff" which evolves into an "incredible soaring chorus."<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.totalguitar.co.uk/page/totalguitar?entry=slipknot_preview_of_all_hope|title= Slipknot: Preview Of All Hope Is Gone|accessdate=2008-08-01 |author= Nick Cracknell |date= 2008-07-24|work= |publisher=[[Total Guitar]]}}</ref> Dan Martin of ''[[The Guardian]]'' compared "Dead Memories" to "[[Enter Sandman]]," while calling "Gematria (The Killing Name)" "astonishingly dense thrash."<ref>{{cite news |first= Dan|last= Martin|title= Rock review: Slipknot, All Hope Is Gone|url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2008/aug/10/slipknot.all.hope.is.gone|work= Pop and Rock|publisher= ''[[The Guardian]]''|date= 2008-08-10|accessdate=2008-08-14}}</ref> Reviewing for [[The Quietus]], John Doran praised "Butcher's Hook," while citing "This Cold Black" as the album's heaviest piece.<ref>{{cite news |first= John|last= Doran|title= Slipknot's All Hope Is Gone Not Just A Clever Name...|url= http://www.thequietus.com/articles/slipknot-s-i-all-hope-is-gone-i-not-just-a-clever-name-says-john-doran|publisher= ''[[The Quietus]]''|date= 2008-08-13|accessdate=2008-08-14}}</ref>

